{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_igglybuff_ver01/data/sn89051213/00414213066/1908052801/0881.xml":{"full_text":"against special\nLEGISLATION\nState Bar Association Raps Arkansas\nLegislature for Spending so Much\nTime Passing Local and\nSpecial Bills.\nLittle Rock, May 22.\u2014The first\nday's session of the Arkansas Bar\nAssociation, which convened yes\nterday morning in the circuit\ncourt room of the Federal build\ning. was marked by an important\nreport of the Committee on Law\nand Law Reforms, which de\nclared that the Arkansas legisla\nture is being more and more\ngoverned by local and special\nlegislation to the detriment of\nthe state. The report was en\ndorsed and an interesting discus\nsion followed its reading. The\ncommittee is composed of John\nFletcher, Thomas C. Me Rea and\n,lohn II, Carmichael. President\nW. II. Arnold of Texarkana\npresided over the convention.\nThe report called attention to\nthe fact that the constitution of\nArkansas provides that \u201cIn all\neases where a general law can be\nmade applicable, no special law\nI shall be enacted\u201d and that \u201cno\nI local or special bill shall be passed\nI unless the notice of the intention\nI to apply therefore shall have been\ni published in the locality to the\nj affected thereby for 30 days.\"\n\u201cSince the decision of the\ncase of Davis vs. Gaines was\nrendered,\u201d continues the report,\n\u201cholding that the action of the\nlegislature is conclusive of any\nquestion that may be raised in\nreference to these provisions of\nI the constitution, they have been\npractically disregarded by the\nlegislature.\u201d\nThe report shows that by the\nlegislature of 1874-7.') 100 bills\nwere passed of which 11 were\ni local and special and 89 were\ngeneral. Only II per cent of the\nwhole number wore special and\n[local. Coming down to the last\nGeneral Assembly, there were en\nacted 174 bills, of which 308 arc\nlocal and special and 100 are\ngeneral. The percentage of local\nand special bills is 02.87 percent.\n\u201cWe can suggest no remedy,\nother than that which appeals to\nthe conscientious discharge of\n|duty bv the individual legisla\ntors,\u201d says the report. \u201cA refer\nence of each local or special bill\nto a proper committee charged\nj wit *i the duty to inquire into the\n[question arising under the con\nstitutional provisions referred to,\nmight go far to correct the evil.\n\u201cWe also suggest that a law\nshould be enacted regulating the\npublication of the notice indicat\ned by the constitution, and a\nproper construction of such an\nact by the Supreme court might\ngo a long way to correct the ap\nparent wrong growing out of the\n|decision in Davis vs. Gaines.\nJ. II. Carmichael of the com\nmittee declared the passing of\nspecial and local bills, is some\nthing akin to bribery. \u201cSuppose\nthat I were representing a certain\nicounty in the legislature and\nwanted something special,\u201d said\nnir. t armiciiaei, \"aim a repie\n'\u2022\u25a0atativo in another county wnnt\n\u00ab'<l a special act for a goose farm.\nIf I vote for his bill and he votes\nfor mine, without cither of us\ni looking into the necessity of the\nI other\u2019s bill, 1 ask if that is right\nThings will come to such a pass\nin this state that if we ih> not\ncheck the passage of special local\nlaws, laws simply representing\nIho w hims, passions or prejudices\nof the legislators, we will burden\nthe state statute books.\"\nSHOT BY PLAYMATE.\nStuart Smith, Aged 8, of Pine Bluff,\nIs Killed.\nPine Bluff, May 21.\u2014Stuart\nSmith, the 8-year-old son of Mr.\nf and Mrs. William J. Smith, PH8\nWest Pullen street, was accident\nally shot and killed today while\nplaying in the woodshed with\n1 some other children who were\ntry ing to cock a 22 caliber revol\nver which they had found. The\nbullet entered near bis right eye\nand he ran out of the shed into\nthe back yard, where he fell dead.\nHis playmates at once ran to theii\nhomes and are so frightened that\n\u2019t cannot be learned in whost\nhands the weapon was when the\naccident occurred. The fathvi\nconducts a grocery store here.\nThe funeral was held Friday\nafternoon ai 3 o\u2019clock from the\nresidence, with the Kev. J. I. Nor\nns, pastor of the Presbytcriai\njchurch, in charge.\nPROHIBITION VICTORY.\nBoth Republican and Democratic Par\nties in Washington Declare for\nConstitutional Amendment.\nSpokane, Wash May 25.\u2014Pro\nhibitionists in Washington are in\nhigh glee today; in fact, they are\njubilant, having won their fight\nagainst the liquor traffic hands\ndown, both the Republican and\nDemocratic parties having adopt\ned platforms lavoring constitu\ntional amendment against the\nmanufacture or sale of liquor.\nJohn Anderson, the foremost\nsupporter of the prohibitionists in\nthe northwest, announces it*is\nprobable that the party will merge\nI its interests with one of the two\ndominant elements or indorse the\nplatlortus of both, giving its ad\nherents the choice between local\noption or absolute prohibition\nlhe prohibitionists polled less\nthan 10 per cent of the state under\nthe new primary law at the last\nelection.\nThe situation presented in\nWashington by the action of the\ndemocratic convention in declar\ning for prohibition is a peculiar\none. The Democrats met here\nseveral days after the close oi the\nRepublican state convention,\nwhich declared itself for William\nII. Taft for the presidency, and\nlocal option. The Democrats in\nstrutted their delegates for Wil\nliam Jennings Bryan and resolved\nin favor of the weighted lid.\nA VERITABLE MENA BOOSTER.\nFort Smith Hears of Mena and Its\nProspects for Railroad.\nThe Rev. George Kirschke,\nsecretary of the Mena Commer\ncial Club, returned Saturday\nfrom Fort Smith. The Times\nof Friday said, in part:\n\u201cAmong those who are in town\nto take in the Musical Festival\nare Hal Norwood, Democratic\nnominee for attorney general and\npresident of the Mena Commer\ncial Club, and Rev. George\nKirschke, who is well known in\nthis city, he haying supplied the\npulpit of the Lutheran church\nhere during the long illness of\nthe late pastor, Rev. Rolfing.\nRev. Kirschke went from here to\nMena to become pastor of the\nLutheran church there and,\nthrough the immigration from\nthe north to that town last year,\nlie has doubled the voting mem\nbets ol his congregation.\n\u201cWith reference to the bustling\ntown of Mena Mr. Ktrsehke is a\nveritable booster, though he has\na very warm spot in his heart for\nFort Smith. He says the town\nis growing fast and that there is\nevery indication that the project\ned railroad from Hot Springs to\nthat place will lie built, in which\nevent the future of the city as a\nmetropolis is assured. The com\nmercial club of that place has\nreceived a letter from Gsorge E.\nCrater, Jr., who seems to be a\npromoter on a very large scale,\nsaying that the road can be fi\nnanced withput any trouble and\nthat he has the confirmation of\ntwo standard financial institutions\nwhich insures the building of the\nI road if the conditions are satis\nj factory.\u201d _\nKILLED BEAR AND WOLVES.\nThad and Isaac Reed Bring in Carcass\nand Six Wolf Scalps Today.\nThad and Isaac Reed, who re\nside out on the Ouachita, drove\ninto Mena Saturday morning,\nbringing with them a large black\ni...ufUipli h n fi shut ;\u00bbnfl\nkilled Friday morning in the\nFourche mountains east of Mena.\nIn addition to the bear killed, a\ncub boar was captured and a den\nof wolves discovered and six\nvountr wolves killed and their\nscalps taken.\nThad Reed, in speaking of this\nj exciting bear and wolt hunt,stated\nthat he and Isaac Reed accom\npanied by J. A. Ford and two\nsons started out Thursday after\nnoon for the Fourche mountains\nto spend Friday hunting wolves,\nwhich are said to be very numer\nous in that section.\nEarly Friday morning the\nparty struck out from camp and\nlit was only a short time until the\ndogs took up the trail and the\nI chase 'vason. About 10 o clock\n.Thad Reed stopped under a tree\nj to rest and on looking down dis\ncovered the bed of a bear and\njust above him, clinging to the\ntrunk of the tree, was a young\ncub. Shortly after making this\ndiscovery Mr. Reed heard a\nrustling in the brush and soon\nthe mother bear was seen rushing\ntoward him ready for a scrap,\nj When at a distance of about\nI twenty feet the animal raised to\njts hind feet, then Mr. Reed\nbrought his gun into action and\nsent a load of buckshot into the\nneck of the bear, killing it almost\ninstantly.\nAfter securing the dead bear,\nthe cub and the scalps of the six\nwolves the party returned home\nmuch elated oyer the day s hunt.\nEvery sort oi Legal Blank of\nthe \u201cLegal Light\u201d kind for sale\nI at The Star office\nNEW RAILROAD\nNOW ASSURED\nLine Between Hot Springs and Mena to\nBe in Operation within a Year if\nNecessary Concessions Are\nGranted.\nHot Springs, Ark., May 25.\u2014\nA railroad line between Hot\nSpringe and Mena is an assured\nreality, providing a right-of-way\nis secured. There seems to be\nlittle question but that this will\nbe done. Funds are at band to\nbegin work immediately. The\nroad will be in active operation\nin rhe course of a year, it is\n{stated, if the necessary conces\nI sions are granted.\nBacking for the construction of\nthe road is assured by George\nj E. Crater, Jr., of London, Eng\nland, a prominent corporation\nla wyer and rail way promoter. He\n:has been sent herewith Engineer\nAlexander Perry by wealthy\ncompanies, who have agreed to\nto furnish the rnonev to construct\nthe road, asking only for a right\nof-way. The corporations he\n\u2022epresents will not equipthe road,\nbut will simply build it. The\ndistance to be covered is about\neighty miles.\nIt it estimated the line will\ne lin f n M t 1m /1 I n t n M 1-n in I.r\nCity more than 100 miles. Under\nexisting conditions goods have to\ncome by way of St. Louis.\nAnother even more important\nobject will be attained in opening\nup valuable territory. The sec\ntion of Arkansas to be traversed\nby the road is rich in forest protW\nucts, such as pine, walnut and\noak timber. Several fertile agri\ncultural valleys will be furnished\nwith an outlet.\nThe Business Men\u2019s league it\nmuch gratified at the trend of\nevents. Dr. E. L. Biggs has\nbeen an important factor in\ngetting Mr. Crater here,\nEDSOOENIeT RUMOR.\nThe President of the Port Arthur\nRoute Says There Will Be no\nChange in Management.\nPresident J. A. Edson of the\nKansas City Southern with Gen\neral Manager W. Coughlin has\nbeen on an inspection tour of the\nsouthern part of the system.\nAt Beaumont Mr. Edson stated:\n\u25a0\u2018The directorate of the road\nwill hold their annual meeting\nthe latter part of this month at\nNew York,\u201d said Mr. Edson,\n\u201cand so far as 1 know I will re\nremain with the road as its presi\ndent and no doubt all the old\nofficers will be re elected. I am\nat a loss to know how the rumor\nthat I was to leave the Port Ar\nthur Route to go with the Mis\nsouri Pacific or any other road\noriginated but you can say that\nthere is absolutely no truth in\nthe report.\n\u201cThe outlook for business gen\nerally this year is good and espe\ncially in the West. Crops in\nMissouri, Kansas and Nebraska\nare looking fine and the harvest\ning season ought to bring a return\nof prosperity. Conditions may i>e\nsomewhat unsettled for a time\nuntil alter me elections, uui me\npanic of last year is now a thing\nof the past and the country gen\nerally ought to he in a very pros\noerous condition this fall.\n\u2018\u2018There is also a gratifying and\ngradual improvement in lumber\nconditions shown by many of the\nclosed-down mills resuming opera\ntions and the railoads will be\nbenefited by again receiving a\nhealthy and normal volume of\nlumber business.\u201d\nW1LHELM1NA INN\nTo Open Mount Mena Resort June 1 for\nSeason of 1908.\nThe above health resort has\nbeen renovated and overhauled\nand will be opened to tho public\nJune 1st. There will be compet\nent people in charge. Board and\naccommodations will be first class\nand at moderate rates. Parties\nand picnics will be entertained at\nany time with twenty-four hours\nnotice. Arrangements have been\nmade for an opening ball the first\nnight. Conveyances will meet\ntrains. Dancing and refresh\nments at expense of house. Par\nticulars on application. 619212\nCap(ured Large Tarantula.\nH. W. Huntress of the Lion\nStore, while out strolling early\nSaturday morning north of town,\nheard a rustling sound in the i\nleaves on the side ot the road and i\nupon investigation discovered a|\nlarge tarantula. After some lit-i\nMe effort Mr. Huntress succeeded I\nin capturing and placing in ai\nbox this large specie of the spider\nwhich he has placed it exhibition\ntn his show window.\n______....... __;_-\u00a3_^-_\nTHREE BODIES FOUND.\nDeep Waters of the White Gives Up\nPart of the Victims of the Clar\nendon Launch Fatality.\nClarendon, May 24.\u2014Today has\nadded another chapter to the fatal\nlaunch jiarty calamity of Tues\nday evening, last yet it has inspir\ned the hope that all the bodies of\nthe victims will be recovered,\nthree having been taken from the\nriver today.\nAt about twoo'clock this morn\ning the watchers on the steam\nboat Alda were rewarded by see\ning a body floating on the water\nin the middle of the river, about\na half mile below where the acci\ndent happened, and upon investi\ngation it proved to be that of Dr.\nA. L. Iiouston. It was imme\ndiately taken from the water and\nbrought to town and found to be\nfairly well preserved.\nA few hours later the watchers\nwere again rewarded by finding\nthe body of Miss Lillian Winfield\nand still later on in the day, the\nbody cf Miss Mattie Counts was\ndiscovered floating down the riyer\nnearly three miles below the placa\nwhere she was drowned.\nBERRY ISSUES ORDERS.\nGeneral Requests Veterans to Attend\nTravelers\u2019 Meeting.\nJames H. Berry, major general\ncommanding the Arkansas Divi\nsion, United Confederate Veter\nans, has issued an order to all\nveterans of the state requesting\nthem to attend the festivities at\nFort Smith on the occasion of the\nannual convention ot the Arkan\nsaw Travelers, to be held there\nJune 4, 5 and 6. The order was\nissued after President L. H.\nMoore of the Travelers\u2019 Associ\nation had invited the veterans to\nparticipate in the festivities.\nThe order issued by General\nBerry is as follows:\n\u201cThe annual meeting of the\nArkansas Travelers will be held\nat Fort Smith June 4, 5 and 6,\n1<X>8, and through its president,\nL. H. Moore, has extended a\ncordial invitation to the Con\nfederate veterans of the division\nto be present and join in the\nfestivities of the occasion.\n\u201cI therefore request all veter\nans of the Arkansas division to\nmake a point of going to Fort\nSmith on the date fixed and re\nport to President L. H. Moore at\nthe Hotel Main for assignment\nto place in the parade June 4, at\n2 o\u2019clock p. m.\n\u201cJames H. Berry.\n\u201cMajor General Commanding.\n\u201cW. M. Watkins, Adjutant\nGeneral and Chief of Stall.\u201d\nNature\u2019s Warning.\n\nArkansas People Must Recognize and\nHeed it.\nKidney ills come quietly my.s-j\nteriously.\nBut nature always warms you\nthrough the urine.\nNotice the kidney secretions.\nSee if the color is unhealthy\u2014\nIf there are settlings and sedi\nment,\nPasses to frequent, scanty, pain\nful.\nIt\u2019s time then to use Doan\u2019s Kid\nney Fills.\nTo award off Bright's disease or;\ndiabetes.\nDoan\u2019s have done great work in\nA r ka nsas.\nMartin Duttlinger. of 515 West\nThird street, Little Kook, Arkan\nsas, says: \u201cFor two years I suffer\ned almost constantly from dull,\nheavy aching through my loins\nand in my kidneys. It was very\npainful for me to stoop or lift any\nthing which caused a strain on the\nmuscles of the back, and the kid-|\nuev secretions were too frequent\nand very highly colored. I took]\nit lot of medicine but it did me lit\ntle, if any, good before 1 found\nout that Doan\u2019s Kidney Pills had\ncured people troubled as I was,;\nThis led me to get a box After\ntwo or three days\u2019 treatment, the\npains began to ieave, the kidney\nsecretions became regular, and in\na very short time 1 was relieved\nof the trouble.\nFor sale by all dealers. Price 50\ncents. Foster-Milburn Co., Buf\nfalo, New York, sole agents for\nthe United States.\nRemember the name Doan\u2019s\u2014|\nand take no other.\nDeath at Rust.\nParties up from Rust Saturday j\n1 morning report the death ot Mrs.\nI Allen, wife of William Allen, j\ni who operates a sawmill at that|\nplace, which occurred Friday j\nafternoon. The remains of Mrs.]\nAllen were buried in the Ku-it j\ncemetery Saturday afternoon.\nB.F. ADKISSON.PROP.\nJOHN DEERE BUGGIES\nAre the ones we think are best for this\ncountry -They stand the jolts- and\nwe have just received a full carload of\nthem.\ns\nOur Furniture Stock\nIs very complete at this time and you will find a\nclass of goods that will be both ornamental and\nsubstantial. i\nLOOK AT OUR FISHING TACKLE\nW. E. Watkins Bro.\nHardware, Furniture aud Farm Implements\nPickering Avenue. Mena, Arkansas.\nIF AN AD in The Star Leads You to a Bargain, Tell the\nMerchant Where You Saw It.","height":"29684","width":"20880"}}
